SIMPLE: expose
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Expose
<hw>Ex*pose"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Exposed</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Exposing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>exposer</ets>; pref.
<ets>ex-</ets> (L. <ets>ex</ets> out)+<ets>poser</ets> to place. See
<er>Pose</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set forth; to
set out to public view; to exhibit; to show; to display; <as>as, to
<ex>expose</ex> goods for sale; to <ex>expose</ex> pictures to public
inspection.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those who seek truth only, freely <qex>expose</qex> their
principles to the test, and are pleased to have them examined.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lay bare; to lay open to attack, danger, or
anything objectionable; to render accessible to anything which may
affect, especially detrimentally; to make liable; <as>as, to
<ex>expose</ex> one's self to the heat of the sun, or to cold, insult,
danger, or ridicule; to <ex>expose</ex> an army to destruction or
defeat.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Expose</qex> thyself to feel what wretches feel.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deprive of concealment; to discover; to lay open
to public inspection, or bring to public notice, as a thing that shuns
publicity, something criminal, shameful, or the like; <as>as, to
<ex>expose</ex> the faults of a neighbor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You only <qex>expose</qex> the follies of men, without arraigning
their vices.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To disclose the faults or reprehensible practices
of; to lay open to general condemnation or contempt by making public the
character or arts of; <as>as, to <ex>expose</ex> a cheat, liar, or
hypocrite</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expose</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
